I"ë!<h1 id="how-to-create-github-pages">How to create GitHub pages</h1>
<p>For developer, the Github Pages seemed to have a prerequisite. Especially for people like me who have no experience in this industry, it seems more necessary.</p>

<p>To make a GitHub blogs, this seemingly really simple work was actually not easy for me. To create this homepage, I had to find out what Git is and know the git command. And I had to know about Jekyll and Markdown, althogh not yet depp. Moreover I had to know Ruby too.</p>

<p>I need to organize what I studied. I‚Äôm going to start with this page.</p>

<hr />
<h2 id="step1-creating-a-repository-on-github">Step1: Creating a repository on Github</h2>
<p>Before you starting, absolutely you need an account of Github. If you don‚Äôt have, create an account.
Then you can see ‚Äò+‚Äô on the top right side of the browser and also you can find the green button which are in the red box on the picture below.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/createPages/step1_0.png" alt="Create a repository" /></p>

<p>Once you click the ‚Äò+‚Äô or New button, then you can create a new repository</p>

<p><img src="/assets/createPages/step1_1.png" alt="New repository" /></p>

<p>Like a webpage which has own name, your repository also needs a special name to generate website.</p>

<p><img src="/assets/createPages/step1_2.png" alt="Namning website" /></p>
<ol>
  <li><strong>The syntax of respository name</strong>
    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code> username.github.io
</code></pre></div>    </div>
    <p>I already created my repository, therefore I put ‚Äútest‚Äù between {username} and {github}
 (username is your actual GitHub username)
 According to <a href="https://docs.github.com/en/pages/getting-started-with-github-pages/creating-a-github-pages-site">GitHub Docs</a>, you must be named user.github.io</p>

    <p>Ref:</p>
    <ol>
      <li><a href="https://guides.github.com/features/pages/">GitHub Guides</a></li>
      <li><a href="https://docs.github.com/en/pages/getting-started-with-github-pages/about-github-pages#types-of-github-pages-sites">About GitHub Pages</a></li>
    </ol>
  </li>
  <li><strong>Select ‚ÄúPublic‚Äù radio button.</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Check ‚ÄúAdd a README file‚Äù</strong></li>
  <li><strong>Click Create repository.</strong></li>
</ol>

<p>Conglats! Now you have a repository.</p>

<hr />
<h2 id="step2-clonning">Step2: Clonning</h2>

<p>I assume that there are many different way to create a pages. My way is below:</p>

<ol>
  <li>
    <p>Firstly, you have to create a folder on your laptop or PC. Go back to your repository page on GitHub</p>

    <p><img src="/assets/createPages/step2_0.png" alt="Clone" /></p>

    <p><strong>Click the Code button</strong></p>

    <p><img src="/assets/createPages/step2_1.png" alt="Clone2" /></p>

    <p><strong>Click the button then it will copy your repository address</strong></p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>Open your shell(Terminal or iterm2)
And set the address where you create a new folder</p>

    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code> git clone [copied address] 
</code></pre></div>    </div>

    <p>e.g.1</p>
    <div class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code> git clone https://github.com/JKsamuel/JKsamuel.github.io.git
</code></pre></div>    </div>

    <p>e.g.2</p>

    <p><img src="/assets/createPages/step2_2.png" alt="example" /></p>
  </li>
</ol>

<p><strong>Done! Easy!</strong></p>

<p>Now, We need to check it is done.
Go to the folder you create for git repositor, you can see the README.md and hidden folder named .git
hidden folder .git is When you init git, then created automatically.</p>

